data.content:
## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### What breaks on .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by the runtime |

### Pattern classification

Your code has **three** overlapping patterns:

1. **Cancellable work loop** — `while (_running)` with `Thread.Abort` as fallback stop
2. **ThreadAbortException as control flow** — catch block rolls back a transaction
3. **Thread.ResetAbort to continue** — keeps the thread alive so `finally` runs

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent of the old ThreadAbortException catch:
                // clean up partial work, then exit the loop gracefully.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // No need for ResetAbort — we control the flow now
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation (replaces Thread.Abort)

        // Wait for the thread to finish — use Join with a timeout
        // instead of Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Key change: make `GetNextItem` cancellation-aware

The original comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." This is the critical part — **`CancellationToken` cannot interrupt a blocking call that doesn't check it**. You must pass the token through:

```csharp
// ❌ Before — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// ✅ After — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If the blocking call is your own `WaitOne`/`Sleep`:
```csharp
// ❌ Thread.Sleep can't be cancelled
Thread.Sleep(5000);

// ✅ Wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
```

### Pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Forgetting to pass the token to blocking calls** | The loop will hang on `GetNextItem()` even after `Cancel()` is called. Cooperative cancellation only works if the blocking code checks the token. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers/callbacks. Always `Dispose()` it. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated exceptions from nested async work. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem()` is long-running, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside it. |
| **Lost cleanup from removing the catch** | The old `ThreadAbortException` catch had `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` — make sure this logic is preserved in the new `OperationCanceledException` catch or a `finally` block. |

### Migration summary

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|----------------|--------|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Remove — you control flow with `break`/`continue` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` + poll | `Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` |
